{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem requires finding a sequence of sibling merges to transform one tree into another. This involves identifying which nodes in the initial tree must be merged to match the structure and node values of the final tree, while respecting the rule that only the larger value survives. This is essentially a tree isomorphism/matching problem with a specific merging constraint.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "tree_structure_analyzer",
      "instructions": "Analyze the relationship between the initial tree and the final tree. For each node in the final tree, identify which node (or set of nodes) in the initial tree corresponds to it. Specifically, determine which siblings in the initial tree must be merged to form a single node in the final tree. A node in the final tree is formed by merging a set of siblings in the initial tree if they all share the same parent and the largest value among them matches the final node's value."
    },
    {
      "label": "merge_sequence_generator",
      "instructions": "Given the mapping of initial sibling sets that must be merged to form final nodes, generate a valid sequence of merge operations. A merge operation (u, v) is valid if u and v are siblings. To ensure the 'larger value survives' rule is respected and to avoid invalid states, suggest a bottom-up approach: merge siblings at the deepest possible level first. For a set of siblings that need to be merged into one, order the merges such that we always merge a smaller value into a larger value, or ensure the sequence of merges results in the correct final set of children for the parent."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent should use the tree_structure_analyzer to map initial nodes to final nodes and identify groups of siblings that must be merged. Then, use the merge_sequence_generator to turn these groups into a specific, ordered list of (u, v) pairs. The final solution must ensure that merges are performed such that we don't attempt to merge nodes that have already been merged or nodes that are no longer siblings due to previous operations. A bottom-up traversal (post-order) is the most reliable way to implement this."
}

